passages.text: Performance: MSCI/All Taiwan \(+1.6\% / + 2.1\%\) , leading MXAPJ by \(2.0\%\) (in US\\$). Capital Goods \((+6\%)\) , Hardware & other Semis \((+4\%)\) and TSMC \((+2\%)\) led, while Energy \((- 8\%)\) , Utilities \((- 4\%)\) , Financials and Telcos \((- 2 - 3\%\) each) lagged. TWD at \(30.6 (+0.1\%\) vs. USD; Exhibit 14)
Valuation: Fwd 12m P/E at \(16.9x(+1.2s.d.;\) Exhibit 17)
EPS Revisions: Consensus 2025/26E EPS \(- 0.1\% / + 0.2\%\) with \(+\) ve revisions in Cap Goods and Semis vs. - ve revisions in Financials and Consumer sectors (Exhibit 23)
Flows: QFIIs net bought US\\$250mn in Tech but net sold US\\$900mn in non- Tech, increased futures net shorts by US\\$400mn, and reduced leveraged ETF exposure.

Domestic funds net bought US\\$500mn across various sectors. Retail investors increased margin longs and purchased both cash equities and futures. ETFs saw muted/- US\\$800mn outflows for dividend/non- div focused (from Exhibit 24)
TSMC ADR premium down to \(23\%\) (- 3pp). Our Premium Reversal Index (SSRTSMR) turned to - 0.1, indicating a largely neutral reversal potential (Exhibit 49)
Cross- Strait Risk: GSSRCSRI up to 75 (Exhibit 52)
Macro Data (July): IP \(+18.1\%\) yoy (vs. Cons \(+17.0\%\) , June \(+18.3\%\) ); Retail Sales \(- 3.6\%\) yoy (vs. June - 2.9%)
Upcoming Data: S&P Global PMI (Mon), Inflation (Fri)

FTSE GEIS Rebalancing: We estimate potential passive inflows of US\\$140 million following the FTSE Global Equity Index Series (GEIS) rebalancing on September 19, which includes four additions and two deletions in the FTSE Taiwan Index, as well as eight stock replacements in the All Cap Index (Exhibit 3). Health Care and Banks may see the largest inflows, while Life Tech could face moderate outflows. We also expect Caliway Biopharm (6919) and King Slide (2059) to replace PharmaEssentia (6446) and TCC (1101) in the FTSE Taiwan TVSE 50 Index.

Foreign Flow Update: QFIIs have turned net sellers (- US\\$4bn) after strong Tech buying from mid- April to early August (+ US\\$25bn, vs. - US\\$1bn in non- Tech). Mutual funds trimmed exposure in July, while hedge funds increased gross exposure in August following stable flows, and continued net buying since mid- July (Exhibit 4).
2Q25 Earnings Wrap: \(22\%\) beats and \(66\%\) misses, primarily due to margin shortfalls (Exhibit 8).
